			<p><orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> Insists on Divorce of a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">Mixed Marriage</term></p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene Hirsch</persName>, born <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Meyer</persName>.</p>
			<p>Born: <date when="1905-11-07">7 November 1905</date> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html"
					>Teplice</placeName>. She remained an only <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
					>child</term>.</p>
			<p>Father: <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-129" type="subject">Ship’s</term> captain on a trade <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-129" type="subject">ship</term>. Of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject">nationality</term>, living in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2911297/free-and-hanseatic-city-of-hamburg.html">Hamburg</placeName>. He <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> in <date when="1908">1908</date>. He and
					<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene’s</persName> mother were divorced shortly before his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term>.</p>
			<p>Mother: <persName ref="#ehri_et_meyer_ella">Ella Meyer</persName>, born <persName ref="#ehri_et_meyer_ella">Kerl</persName>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741" type="subject">married</term> in <date when="1904">1904</date>. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741" type="subject">Married</term> for a second time in <date when="1922"
					>1922</date> to a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-930" type="subject">banker</term> named <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_perutz">Perutz</persName> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene’s</persName> mother continued to run the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">boarding house</term> founded by the grandmother, Mrs
					<persName ref="#ehri_et_kerl_marie">Marie Kerl</persName>, after her <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term>. <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene"
					>Helene</persName> spent her childhood and youth here until her <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741"
					type="subject">marriage</term>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene's</persName> mother <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745"
					type="subject">died</term> from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-217" type="subject">suicide</term>
				on <date when="1945-06-06">6 June 1945</date> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html"
				>Teplice</placeName>.</p>
			<p>Native country: Through her father’s <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject"
					>nationality</term>: <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">Germany</placeName>.</p>
			<p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-724" type="subject">Religion</term>: <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-771" type="subject">Evangelical</term>. Her mother was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-767" type="subject">Catholic</term>.</p>
			<p>Due to her mother’s contact with Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject"
					>people</term>, as a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> mainly had Jewish friends throughout her <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1134" type="subject">school</term> years. The other <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1134" type="subject">schoolgirls</term> resented her for this, which
				later led to a strong sense of isolation, especially in the dance <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1134"
					type="subject">classes</term>. One lifelong friendship with a Jewish girl began <q>in the pram.</q></p>
			<p>It was not unusual in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName> for Jews and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christians</term> to meet, since the well-off <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish population</term> held a fairly dominant
				position. Furthermore, many Jewish boarders were living in <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene's</persName> grandmother’s
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">house</term> (later her mother’s), so friendly
				relations began quite naturally.chr</p>
			<p>As a young <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term>, through her interest in
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-709" type="subject">sport</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> mostly socialised with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term> groups. She was well-known as a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-709" type="subject">tennis player</term>. A close friendship with a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term> built up on this basis. With time however,
				this changed and at the age of 25 <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">married</term> a Jewish <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term> who was born in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName>. When the engagement was announced, <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> was annoyed by the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term> and the Jewish <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">families</term> alike in that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christians</term> found it wrong that she should <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">marry</term> a Jew, and the Jews found this Jew
				socially beneath her. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741" type="subject">marriage</term> was
				however <q>especially good</q> – until <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000185">Hitler</persName>
				and the circumstances created by him interfered.</p>
			<p>The husband, <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon Hirsch</persName>, was a top <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-941" type="subject">insurance</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">agent</term> at the <q><orgName
						ref="#ehri_et_viktoria">Viktoria</orgName></q>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-928" type="subject">company</term>. He got a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">job</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3068031/podmokly.html">Bodenbach</placeName>, where the young couple relocated (<date when="1930"
					>1930</date>). There they only had contact with Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207"
					type="subject">people</term>, the Jews and the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject"
					>Christians</term> did not socialise. They did have one non-Jewish acquaintance, a colleague of <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon’s</persName> who often came to their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">house</term>. He was resented for this by the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term> side.</p>
			<pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-WL16560939_03.jpg"/>
			<p>In <date when="1933">1933</date>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon</persName> was moved to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3073803/karlovy-vary.html"
					>Karlsbad</placeName>, which was an improvement in every way. They felt so happy there that <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon"
					>Egon</persName> did not want to leave the place when in <date when="1938">1938</date>
				<persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000185">Hitler</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1041" type="subject">annexed</term> the <placeName
					ref="#ehri_et_sudetenland">Sudentenland</placeName> and almost all Jews fled to (at that time still safe) <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>. But <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName>
				finally managed to persuade him, so they both went to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>
				leaving everything behind in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3073803/karlovy-vary.html">Karlsbad</placeName>. The atmosphere
				there in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-872" type="subject">Jewish community</term> was extremely
				depressing and <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon</persName> and <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> felt
				altogether so unhappy that they returned to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3073803/karlovy-vary.html">Karlsbad</placeName>.
				But not for long! After a week the situation in the <placeName ref="#ehri_et_sudetenland">Sudentenland</placeName> got so much worse
				that they again <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">fled</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>, this time for good. In <date when="1939">1939</date>
				however, <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000185">Hitler</persName> also <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-632" type="subject">occupied</term>
				<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>. <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene"
					>Helene</persName> assessed the situation more accurately than her husband and she pulled out all the stops to make it possible
				for them both to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">emigrate</term>. In her spirited
				manner she went directly with <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon’s</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1141" type="subject">passport</term> to the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> and in order to get him a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1142" type="subject">permit</term> to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">leave the country</term>, she came up with the excuse
				that he wanted to visit his sick mother-in-law. She also managed to get him a ticket, and so he was able to make the journey to
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/6269131/england.html">England</placeName>. <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene"
					>Helene</persName> herself was not granted <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1142" type="subject"
					>permission</term> to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">leave</term>, since as a
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term> she was not allowed to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">leave the country</term>. Her <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1141" type="subject">passport</term> was even taken away and she only got
				it back two months later. She kept trying, but when she finally was allowed to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">leave the country</term>, she did not get the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1146" type="subject">visa</term> for <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/6269131/england.html">England</placeName>, so had to stay in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>. Until he left in <date when="1939-03">March 1939</date>,
					<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon</persName> was able to continue <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">working</term> for his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-928" type="subject">insurance company</term>
				<orgName ref="#ehri_et_viktoria">Viktoria</orgName> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html"
				>Prague</placeName>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741" type="subject">marriage</term> was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-582" type="subject">dissolved</term> upon the orders of the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> once <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon"
					>Egon’s</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1141" type="subject">passport</term> had arrived from <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/6269131/england.html">England</placeName>.</p>
			<p>Until <date when="1946">1946</date> when <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> was finally able to join her husband
				living in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2643743/london.html">London</placeName>, her life went by as follows: Since in
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czechoslovakia</placeName> there was labour conscription, she
				looked for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> although she did not have the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-934" type="subject">financial</term> need to. <pb n="4"
					facs="EHRI-ET-WL16560939_04.jpg"/> She joined a <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3077311/czechia.html">Czech</placeName>
				lawyer who needed to take on someone who could speak <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html"
					>German</placeName>, where she <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> in
				office service. After she had been <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">working</term>
				there about a year, she gave up the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">job</term> and,
				as she was used to doing, went for a few weeks to do winter <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-709"
					type="subject">sports</term> in the mountains. This surprising fact was brought about by a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-286" type="subject">doctor’s</term> certificate stating that she had <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">TB</term>. The reasoning given was that the X-ray
				image showed a healed over shadow and the longstanding slightly <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292"
					type="subject">raised temperatures</term> were indicative of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292"
					type="subject">TB</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">lung
					disease</term> of an aunt who had <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term>
				early was also put to use for this purpose. In fact <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene Hirsch</persName> never had any such
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">disease</term>, but the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">employment office</term> never made any difficulties
				for her, neither this first time, nor over any of the other various later <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-280" type="subject">medical</term> certificates. Also, at a time when she
				was supposed to go to the ammunitions <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject"
				>factory</term>, she was exempted. She <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term>
				in various roles, either where the employment of a <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html"
					>German</placeName> was required, or else, as in the case of <orgName ref="#ehri_et_viktoria">Viktoria</orgName>, where in view of
					<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon’s</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> there, they wanted to help her. On one
				occasion she found employment through a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject"
					>Christian</term> manager who had declared his Jewish wife as a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374"
					type="subject">half Jew</term>, felt insecure and wanted to hire anyone who he knew to have an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-178" type="subject">anti-Nazi</term> stance. <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> used these various <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">jobs</term>, where opportunities always arose, to
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-253" type="subject">sabotage</term> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">Germans</placeName>. She also <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">sheltered</term> a Jewish acquaintance in her place of
				living for a while. He had come to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> after his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term> wife had driven him out of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2761367/wien.html">Vienna</placeName>. He was eventually discovered and sent to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="camp">Theresienstadt</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration camp</term> where he <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-217" type="subject">took his own life</term> by touching electrically
				charged barbed wire.</p>
			<p>A month and a half before the end of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> was able to go to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName> to see her mother with a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-578" type="subject">certificate</term> from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">employment</term> office, again acknowledging her <pb
					n="5" facs="EHRI-ET-WL16560939_05.jpg"/>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">tuberculosis</term>. She had to attend a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-286" type="subject">doctor</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName>, who gave her very painful injections against the supposed
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">disease</term>, but she wanted to stay in
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName> so she had to put herself through that.</p>
			<p>Two months after the peace agreement, when the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/8354411/union-of-soviet-socialist-republics.html">Russians</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-632" type="subject">occupied</term>
				<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName>, the two <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> (the mother was still alive) took
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3017382/republic-of-france.html">French</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-511" type="subject">prisoners of war</term> under their protection in
				their <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">house</term>. Apart from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-829" type="subject">fear</term> of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/8354411/union-of-soviet-socialist-republics.html">Russians</placeName>, they were also troubled by
				the possibility of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term>, and this
				drove the mother to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-217" type="subject">suicide</term>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> was one of the first to be able to go to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/6269131/england.html">England</placeName>. She profusely thanked an <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/6269131/england.html">English</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">lady</term>, a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-763" type="subject">Christian</term>, who had readily accepted <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon</persName>, for her tireless efforts. Since <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon">Egon</persName>
				had always declared himself to the authorities in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/6269131/england.html">England</placeName> as
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741" type="subject">married</term>, it was soon possible to get the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-741" type="subject">marriage</term>, which had only been <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-582" type="subject">dissolved</term> under the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1063" type="subject">Nazi regime</term>, legally valid again. As it turned
				out however, due to the fact that their experiences over the seven years of their separation had estranged them so much from one
				another, after three years together, <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> and <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_egon"
					>Egon</persName> again divorced. Afterwards, like almost all <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304"
					type="subject">refugees</term>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene</persName> tried a wide variety of types of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term>. In <date when="1947">1947</date> she
				eventually got a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">job</term> as a secretary for the
				European Service of the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004997">BBC</orgName>, where she still <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">works</term> today.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_hirsch_helene">Helene's</persName> possessions and the large <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">house</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3064288/teplice.html">Teplice</placeName> were lost through the circumstances without any prospect of
